{"cursor":"30827","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Cosmopolitanism' is the ideology that all human ethnic groups belong to a\nsingle community based on a shared morality. Cosmopolitanism may entail some\nsort of world government or it may simply refer to more inclusive moral,\neconomic, and/or political relationships between nations or individuals of\ndifferent nations. A person who adheres to the idea of cosmopolitanism in any of\nits forms is called a 'cosmopolitan' or 'cosmopolite'.\n\nA cosmopolitan community might be based on an inclusive morality, a shared\neconomic relationship, or a political structure that encompasses different\nnations. In its more positive versions, the cosmopolitan community is one in\nwhich individuals from different places (e.g. nation-states) form relationships\nof mutual respect. As an example, Kwame Anthony Appiah suggests the possibility\nof a cosmopolitan community in which individuals from varying locations\n(physical, economic, etc.) enter relationships of mutual respect despite their\ndiffering beliefs (religious, political, etc.). Kwame Anthony Appiah,\n\"Cosmopolitan Patriots,\" Critical Inquiry 23, no. 3 (Spring, 1997): 617-\n639.\n","linknr":548,"url":"Cosmopolitanism","recorded":1362574486,"links":66,"instances":["disambiguation","politics","stoic"],"pdf":["http://www.gtinitiative.org/documents/PDFFINALS/15Movements.pdf","http://www.sussex.ac.uk/Users/ssfa2/cosmo%20pq.pdf","http://www.gtinitiative.org/documents/PDFFINALS/15Movements.pdf","http://www.lse.ac.uk/collections/sociology/pdf/Beck-LivingintheWorldRiskSociety-Feb2006.pdf"],"categories":["Human migration","Political theories","Politics and race","Political philosophy","Social philosophy","Philosophical movements","Social movements","Cultural geography","World government","Philosophical schools and traditions","Interculturalism","Global civics"],"headings":["Etymology","Philosophical cosmopolitanism","Contemporary cosmopolitan thinkers","Political 